Orasema smithi Howard, 1896: 134
. n. syn. Type material: Grenada : Balthazar ( Windward side), W.I. H.H. Smith. W. Indies. 99–331
. 1 ♀, BMNH: type no. 5.372).

caption.paragraph:
FIGURES 139–144.
Orasema minutissima .
♀: Dominica: 139. Habitus. 140. Head. 141. Antenna, with F2 plus pedicel, and F6–F7 inset. 142. Mesosoma of “small” form, dorsal view. 143. Mesosoma of “large” form, dorsal view. 144. Axillula.

subSubSection.paragraph: Diagnosis. Head and mesosoma mostly or entirely blue to purple. Mesoscutal midlobe and mesoscutellar disc mostly reticulate. Axillula with parallel longitudinal carinae, with some reticulate sculpture as well. Fore femur with brown coloration.

Small specimens of this species are easily recognized, due to the distinctive dark multiporous plate sensilla of the antennal flagellum ( Fig. 141 ). They are also recognizable by gestalt, in having protruding mesoscutal sidelobes and reticulate mesoscutal and mesoscutellar sculpture ( Figs 142, 143 ). Large specimens have a distinctive mesoscutal midlobe ( Fig. 143 ), but are rarely collected and do not closely resemble small specimens.
Orasema costaricensis
and
O. rapo
differ in that their mesoscutal sidelobes are not protruding ( Figs 45 , 190–192 ).
Orasema evansi
differs in having pale multiporous plate flagellar sensilla ( Figs 63 , 71 ), and in lacking reticulate sculpture on its axillula ( Figs 65 , 73 ). However, smaller specimens of these species (about 2.5 mm in length) can be very difficult to distinguish from
O. minutissima
.

caption.paragraph:
FIGURES 145–146.
Orasema minutissima .
♀: Dominica: 145. Stigma and postmarginal vein. 146. Propodeum, pedicel, hind coxae of “small” form.

subSubSection.paragraph: Description. Female. Length 1.2–3.1 mm . Females of the "small" morph are up to 1.5 mm long. Females of the medium/large morph are 2.3 mm and longer.

Color: Head and mesosoma in larger specimens blue green dorsally, becoming purple to black laterally, but in smaller specimens mainly brown with faint metallic luster; pronotum reddish brown in smaller specimens. Pedicel yellow to yellowish-brown; anellus yellow to yellowish-brown; flagellum yellow to yellowish-brown. Coxae brown with faint metallic luster dorsally, becoming yellow apically; fore femur brown; mid femur yellow or brown; hind femur yellow. Fore wing hyaline; venation yellowish to pale brown. Petiole blue-green, almost entirely brown in smaller specimens; gaster pale brown to dark brown, with blue-green luster, acrosternite dark brown to black.

Head: Head width:head height 1.1–1.2; face reticulate; longitudinal groove between eye and torulus present, indistinct in larger specimens; eyes bare, inter-ocular distance:eye height 1.4–1.5; malar space:eye height 0.6–0.7; supraclypeal area longer than broad, smooth in ventral triangular area, otherwise weakly sculptured; clypeus weakly sculptured. Flagellum length:head height 1.2–1.4; F2 1.8–2.5× as long as broad, 1.0–1.3× as long as F3; following funiculars subequal in width, progressively shorter in larger specimens, progressively shorter and broader in smaller specimens.

Mesosoma: Mesosoma length:height 1.3–1.4. Mesoscutal midlobe areolate-reticulate, with minute setae; lateral lobe areolate-reticulate. Axilla areolate-reticulate; mesoscutellar disc areolate-reticulate; frenal line regularly foveate; frenum areolate-reticulate; axillular groove anteriorly absent, broad and foveate posteriorly; axillula areolate-reticulate, with parallel longitudinal carinae. Propodeum with irregular median carina; propodeal disc areolate-reticulate; callus areolate-reticulate, with 3–5 setae. Mesepisternum areolate-reticulate laterally, areolate ventrally, broadly rounded anterior to mid coxa. Upper mesepimeron smooth; lower mesepimeron reticulate to very weakly reticulate; transepimeral sulcus distinct. Metepisternum laterally smooth dorsally, reticulate ventrally. Hind coxa 1.8–2.6× as long as broad; hind femur 5.2–6.3× as long as broad. Fore wing 2.3– 3.4× as long as broad, 2.4–2.8× as long as mesothorax; stigma with 4 sensilla in a row or separated into pairs. Hind wing costal cell with a broad bare area.
Metasoma: Petiole 1.5–2.3× as long as broad, 0.7–1.0× as long as hind coxa, areolate, anterior carina moderate. Antecostal sulcus crossed by minute carinae; acrosternite posteriorly angulate.

Male. Length 1.3–2.0 mm. Head width:head height 1.2–1.3; scape yellow; flagellum length:head height 1.7– 1.9, F2 1.7–2.1× as long as broad. All femora and tibiae yellow. Petiole 5.1–6.2× as long as broad, petiole length:hind coxa length 1.8–1.9.

Immature Stages ( Figs 4C, J ). First Instar ( Fig. 4C ). Unfed planidum similar to
O. evansi
(cf. Fig. 21 ), but with more extensive surface wrinking on tergites. Pupa ( Fig. 4J ) with three dorsal tubercles over petiolar region; metasomal tergites with single transverse raised bands, with a sublateral tubercle on Mt1. Other stages, which are known but not described herein appear the same as in
O. evansi
.

Biology.
Orasema minutissima
is by far the most commonly collected species of
Orasema
from the West Indies ( Fig. 3 , insets for small and medium to large forms). The majority of specimens are female, and of the specimens documented below, 1107 are female and only 22 male (19 small and 3 medium). Males are known from a diverse geographic area throughout the Caribbean. No males are present among the relatively few
O. minutissima
collected from outside of the Caribbean. Size variation of
O. minutissima
falls into three apparent classes associated with different hosts. The small morph is a known parasitoid of Wasmannia auropunctata ( Mann 1918 ; Heraty 1994b ) and Wasmannia sigmoidea ( Heraty 1994b ; Wetterer & Porter 2003 ) in the Caribbean. The larger morphs are likely associated with different castes or gynes of the polymorphic
Pheidole
, with the largest morphs assumed to parasitize developing queens or soldiers. We were able to rear and sequence the largest morph from an unidentified species of
Pheidole
( Dominica ). The small morphs are common throughout the Caribbean including Trinidad . We were able to sequence two specimens from Gorgona Island off the coast of Colombia that are identical in genotype to Caribbean populations in Cuba , Dominica , St. Lucia , Tortola and Trinidad . Medium to large sized morphs with an identical genotype are known from Dominica , Guadeloupe and St. Lucia . Beyond size and host differences, there are behavioral differences that have been observed for populations in Dominica . JMH has collected both the medium and small sized morphs in the same vicinity, but never on the same host plant and never together in the same collection (can be separated by as little as 10 meters and with high populations in both areas). The small morph has been found in Dominica ovipositing on ferns (
Cyathea tenera (J.E. Smith) Moore
, Cyathaceae;
Nephrolepis biserrata Schott
, Nephrolepidaceae ;
Thelypteris opposita (Vahl) Ching
, Thelypteridaceae ), whereas the larger size morphs preferentially oviposit on a variety of short (6-12” high) broadleaf plants (
Coccoloba uvifera
L., Polygonaceae ;
Simarouba amara Aublet
, Simaroubaceae ; miscellaneous Fabaceae and Rubiaceae ). Other potential host plants (of the small morph) include
Zapoteca
? formosa (Kunth) H.M. Herm. ( Fabaceae ) and
Gynerium sagittatus (Aubl.) P.Beaub.
( Poaceae ) from Jamaica .

Distribution ( Fig. 2 ). Colombia , Costa Rica , Cuba , Dominica , Dominican Republic , Ecuador , Grenada , Guadeloupe , Guyana , Jamaica , Martinique , Nevis , Puerto Rico , St. Kitts , St. Lucia , St. Maarten , St. Thomas, St. Vincent , Tortola , Trinidad .
